I have been on vacation and am trying to catch up with what&#39;s been going on.

I agree with Moira.  I use all three sounds:  Awl, Ah and On.  In fact, 
I really don&#39;t understand what some people mean when they say they can&#39;t 
hear the difference between Awl and On.  It strikes me in a similar way 
as if they said they can&#39;t distinguish between blue and green.  
Obviously,  the boundary between the two colors is somewhat ambiguous, 
but most of us have a clear enough idea of what blue is versus what 
green is.

I have thought that those who say they can&#39;t hear the difference 
actually just means they don&#39;t use the Awl sound, i.e. they pronounce 
words such as &quot;all&quot; with the On sound.  I expect that they can hear the 
difference if they listen closely to someone pronouncing Awl versus On 
even if it is not a distinction they make in their own speech. 

This whole thread seems to have started as a method to enable a 
dictionary to have all spelling variants placed together 
alphabetically.  Rather than throwing out a phoneme that many of us feel 
quite strongly about, it makes more sense to me that if there is a 
variant spelling that will not be next to the others simply put in a 
note directing the reader to the other spelling as in:  &quot;see also: _______.&quot;

I also feel strongly about the continued availability of &quot;Wh&quot;.  I am 
sure that those who don&#39;t use it don&#39;t miss it, but I can assure you 
reading the QS news with nary a &quot;wh&quot; to be seen is noticed by me every 
time I come across a word where I would use it.  I actually seem more 
aware of its absence in writing than I am in hearing others who don&#39;t 
use &quot;wh&quot; in their speech.

Paige

